<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="395" pageId="1" pageNumber="394" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1796,2039]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,150,321]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="395" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1796,1822]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The upper inner facets distinctly bigger than lower outer facets. Katepisternal seta 1+(2-3); anepimeron, katepimeron and meron bare. M vein straight; the apical of subcosta are not curved and relatively straight. Based on the previous characteristics, the genus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yang &amp; Xue &amp; Tong" authorityYear="2022" box="[614,740,1868,1894]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Chuntiania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="394" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[614,740,1868,1894]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Chuntiania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<emphasis box="[887,982,1869,1894]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Potamia</emphasis>
, but differs from the latter by the frontal seta distributed in the lower half of frons, never upwards near the ocellar triangle; the distal half of the frons bare and orbital seta absent; prosternum bare; posterior dorsocentral seta 3-4; 
<emphasis box="[975,1014,1941,1966]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">pra</emphasis>
absent; posterodorsal surface of hind coxa bare; apical femur without teeth or spurs; hind tibia without posterodorsal seta; distal part of posterior cercus without lateral or interior protuberance, the distal part become narrow and tonguelike (
<figureCitation box="[1142,1239,2012,2038]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,253,1726,1750]" captionTargetBox="[161,1427,1058,1692]" captionTargetId="figure-1180@1.[151,1436,1047,1701]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. The morphological comparison diagram of the male cerci in posterior view of Chuntiania and motamia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6644676" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6644676/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Figure 1</figureCitation>
); the surstylus is elongated and narrow in the middle, 4 or 8 times its length at its narrowest point (in 
<emphasis box="[1089,1184,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">Potamia</emphasis>
is at most 2.5 times as wide as long); and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yang &amp; Xue &amp; Tong" authorityYear="2022" box="[364,490,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Chuntiania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="395" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[364,490,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">Chuntiania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has no postgonite.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="395" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,150,321]" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,223,249]" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yang &amp; Xue &amp; Tong" authorityYear="2022" box="[551,677,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Chuntiania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="395" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[551,677,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">Chuntiania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is after Prof. Chuntian Zhang, in honour of his contributions to entomology.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
